    <div class="img-1">
      <div class="section section-1">
        <h1>Benifits Of Eating Healthy Foods</h1>
        <div class="box1">
          <br>
          Nutrient-Rich: Healthy foods provide essential nutrients such as vitamins, minerals, fiber, and antioxidants
          that are necessary for
          proper bodily functions and overall health<br><br>
        Improved Heart Health: Healthy foods, particularly those high in fiber and low in saturated fats, 
        can lower cholesterol levels and reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke.<br><br>
        Better Digestive Health: Foods high in fiber, such as fruits, vegetables, and whole grains, 
        promote healthy digestion and can prevent constipation and other digestive issues.<br><br>
        Stronger Immune System: A well-balanced diet supports a healthy immune system,
          helping your body fight off infections and illnesses more effectively. <br><br>
        Better Skin Health: Eating a diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and healthy fats can improve skin health,
         reducing the risk of acne and promoting a more youthful appearance.<br><br>
       Longer Lifespan: Research suggests that individuals who follow a healthy diet tend to live longer and 
          have a lower risk of premature death compared to those with poor dietary habits.<br><br>
          </div>
    </div>
  </div>

    <div class="section section-2">
      <h1>Facts:</h1>
      <div class="box2">
        macronutrients like carbohydrates, proteins, and fats get a lot of attention,
         micronutrients such as vitamins and minerals are equally crucial for overall health and well-being.
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="img-2">
        <div class="section section-11">
          <h1>
            India is a country with wide diversity, not only in terms of culture and language but also in 
            terms of dietary habits and nutritional needs. Each state in India has its own unique cuisine,
             influenced by factors such as geography, climate, culture, and availability of ingredients. 
             Here's a brief overview of nutrition and health considerations in different states of India and
              some general tips on how to maintain good health:
          </h1>
          <div class="box4">
            <p>
              Tamil Nadu: Tamil Nadu's cuisine is known for its variety of rice-based dishes like dosa, idli, and sambar. These foods are rich in carbohydrates and proteins, providing energy for daily activities. However, excessive consumption of refined grains and spicy foods may lead to digestive issues and weight gain.
              <br><br>
  Assam: Assamese cuisine includes a variety of rice-based dishes, along with fish, meat, and leafy greens. Fish is a staple protein source, while leafy greens like spinach and mustard greens provide essential vitamins and minerals. However, traditional cooking methods often involve liberal use of oil and spices, so it's important to practice moderation.
  <br><br>
  Rajasthan: Rajasthan's cuisine is influenced by its arid climate and limited availability of fresh vegetables. Dishes like dal baati churma and gatte ki sabzi are hearty and nutritious, providing a good balance of carbohydrates, proteins, and fats. However, excessive consumption of fried foods and sweets should be avoided.
            </p>
      <div class="box3">
        <p>
          Punjab: Punjab is known for its rich and hearty cuisine, which includes dishes like sarson da saag, makki di roti, and tandoori chicken. These dishes are often high in calories, carbohydrates, and fats. While delicious, it's important to consume them in moderation to avoid weight gain and related health issues.
<br><br>
Kerala: Kerala's cuisine is largely influenced by its abundant coastal resources. Traditional dishes like fish curry, appam, and puttu are rich in seafood, coconut, and spices. These foods provide essential fatty acids, vitamins, and minerals. However, coconut-based dishes can be high in saturated fats, so it's important to balance them with other nutritious foods.
<br><br>
West Bengal: Bengali cuisine is characterized by its use of fish, rice, and mustard oil. Fish is a rich source of protein and omega-3 fatty acids, which are beneficial for heart health. However, excessive consumption of fried foods and sweets like roshogolla and mishti doi can contribute to health problems like obesity and diabetes.
<br><br>
Gujarat: Gujarati cuisine is predominantly vegetarian and includes dishes like dhokla, khichdi, and thepla. These foods are often high in fiber, vitamins, and minerals due to the use of ingredients like lentils, vegetables, and whole grains. However, some dishes may be high in oil and sugar, so it's important to make healthier choices.

        </p>
       
        </div>
</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section section-3">
      
      <h1>Tips for Maintaining Good Health:</h1>
      <div class="box2b">
      <p>
        Balanced Diet: Aim for a balanced diet that includes a variety of foods from different food groups, such as fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats.<br>
        <br>Limit Processed Foods: Minimize consumption of processed and packaged foods, which are often high in unhealthy fats, sugars, and sodium.<br>
      </p>
    </div>
    </div>
    <div class="img-3">
      <div class="box6">
        <p>
          Heart Disease:<br>

Omega-3 fatty acids found in fatty fish (such as salmon, mackerel, and trout), flaxseeds, chia seeds, and walnuts can help reduce inflammation and lower the risk of heart disease.
<br>Soluble fiber found in oats, beans, lentils, fruits, and vegetables can help lower cholesterol levels. </p>
    </div>
      <div class="box5">
        <p>
          Diabetes:<br>

          Complex carbohydrates found in whole grains, legumes, and non-starchy vegetables provide steady energy and help regulate blood sugar levels.
          <br>Foods rich in soluble fiber, such as oats, barley, and legumes, can help improve blood sugar control.</p>
  </div>
     <div class="box7">
      Cancer:<br>

      Antioxidant-rich foods like berries, leafy green vegetables, nuts, seeds, and legumes can help protect cells from damage and reduce the risk of certain cancers.
      <br>Cruciferous vegetables such as broccoli, cauliflower, and Brussels sprouts contain compounds that may help prevent cancer.</p>
</div>
<div class="box6">
  <p>
    High Blood Pressure (Hypertension):<br>

Potassium-rich foods like bananas, sweet potatoes, spinach, and beans can help regulate blood pressure.<br>
Magnesium-rich foods such as nuts, seeds, whole grains, and leafy green vegetables can also support healthy blood pressure levels.</p>
</div>
<div class="box5">
  <p>
    Inflammation:<br>

    Omega-3 fatty acids found in fatty fish, flaxseeds, chia seeds, and walnuts can help reduce inflammation.<br>
    Antioxidant-rich foods like berries, leafy greens, nuts, and seeds can also help combat inflammation.</p>
</div>


<div class="box7">
    <p>Calcium for Bone Health:<br>
       Calcium is essential for maintaining strong bones and teeth, as well as for proper muscle function and nerve transmission.<br>
        Adequate calcium intake throughout life, especially during childhood and adolescence when bones are growing, can help prevent osteoporosis later in life.</p>
</div>
</div>
    <div class="section section-4">
      <h1>Why Nutrition is important :</h1>
      <div class="box2">
        Nutritional deficiencies lead to impaired growth, weakened immunity, anemia, bone disorders, vision problems, cognitive impairment, and increased risk of chronic diseases.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="img-4">
      <div class ="box8">

      <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Nutritional Deficiency</th>
            <th>How to Overcome</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Iron Deficiency</td>
            <td>Eat iron-rich foods like red meat, beans, nuts; consider iron supplements under medical guidance.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Vitamin D Deficiency</td>
            <td>Get sunlight exposure, consume vitamin D-rich foods like fatty fish, fortified dairy products.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Vitamin C Deficiency</td>
            <td>Eat citrus fruits, strawberries, bell peppers, broccoli, or take vitamin C supplements.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Vitamin A Deficiency</td>
            <td>Consume foods rich in beta-carotene like carrots, sweet potatoes, spinach, or take supplements.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Vitamin B12 Deficiency</td>
            <td>Eat animal products, fortified cereals, consider B12 injections or supplements if deficient.</td>
        </tr>
      <tr>
          <td>Calcium Deficiency</td>
          <td>Consume dairy products, leafy greens, nuts, seeds; consider calcium supplements if needed.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
          <td>Potassium Deficiency</td>
          <td>Eat bananas, oranges, tomatoes, potatoes, leafy greens, beans, fish, poultry, and dairy.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
          <td>Magnesium Deficiency</td>
          <td>Eat nuts, seeds, whole grains, green leafy vegetables, legumes, and seafood.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
          <td>Omega-3 Fatty Acid Deficiency</td>
          <td>Include fatty fish (salmon, mackerel), flaxseeds, chia seeds, walnuts, and algae supplements.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
          <td>Zinc Deficiency</td>
          <td>Consume meat, shellfish, legumes, seeds, nuts, dairy, whole grains, and fortified cereals.</td>
      </tr>
    </table>
